revision.text:
'''Ambulatory Patient Group''' ('''APG''') is a classification system for [[outpatient]] services reimbursement developed for the American [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] service by the [[Health Care Financing Administration]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Abbey | first1 = Duane C. |last2=Blount |first2=L. Lamar | title = Understanding the financial implications of APGs - ambulatory patient groups | journal = Healthcare Financial Management | date = October 1996 |volume=50 |issue=10 | url= http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/9610251771/understanding-financial-implications-apgs}}</ref> It classifies patients into nearly 300 pathology groups rather than the 14,000 of the [[ICD|International Classification of Diseases]].
The APG system is similar to the [[diagnosis-related group]]s (DRG), which apply to inpatient care rendered by a hospital.
